<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/list-of-sp-500-companies-wikipedia" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>List of S&P 500 Companies</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">An authoritative directory of the top publicly traded U.S. companies driving the economy.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="content-section">
      <p>When investors search for the <strong>list of s&p 500 companies wikipedia</strong>, they are generally looking for a comprehensive, easy-to-read reference detailing the cornerstone of the US equity market. The Standard & Poor's 500, commonly known as the S&P 500, is a stock market index tracking the stock performance of 500 of the largest companies listed on stock exchanges in the United States.</p>
      <p>It is widely regarded as one of the best single gauges of large-cap U.S. equities. Unlike the Dow Jones Industrial Average, which contains only 30 companies and is price-weighted, the S&P 500 is market-capitalization-weighted, meaning that the largest companies by market cap have the greatest influence on the index's performance.</p>
      <p>In this guide, we provide a robust and filterable directory featuring a significant subset of the major index movers. We include current metrics such as price, market capitalization, and sector classification, ensuring you have the data you need for your market research. Understanding the composition of this index is crucial for any investor, whether you are picking individual stocks from our <a href="/top-stocks-to-invest-in-2025">top stocks to invest in 2025</a> list or simply buying a broad market ETF.</p>
      <p>The companies that make up the S&P 500 represent a vast array of industries, providing a panoramic view of the American economy. From technology behemoths and financial institutions to healthcare providers and consumer goods manufacturers, the index's diversity is a key reason it is used as a benchmark by portfolio managers worldwide.</p>
      <p>To be eligible for inclusion in the S&P 500, a company must meet several stringent criteria. It must be a U.S. company, have a market capitalization of at least $15.8 billion (as of recent rules, though this threshold changes), be highly liquid, have a public float of at least 50% of its shares outstanding, and its most recent quarter's earnings and the sum of its trailing four consecutive quarters' earnings must be positive.</p>

