      <p>When searching for the <a href="/best-stocks-to-buy-now">best stocks to buy now</a>, many investors look closely at sector rotations within the S&P 500. During economic expansions, cyclical sectors like Consumer Discretionary and Industrials tend to outperform. In contrast, during economic downturns, defensive sectors like Utilities and Consumer Staples often hold up better because demand for their products and services remains relatively stable.</p>
      <h2>How the Index is Managed</h2>
      <p>The S&P 500 is not a static list; it is a dynamic index maintained by the S&P Dow Jones Indices U.S. Index Committee. This committee meets regularly to review the index's composition and make necessary changes. Companies are added and removed based on the eligibility criteria mentioned earlier, as well as corporate actions like mergers, acquisitions, and spin-offs.</p>
      <p>When a company is added to the S&P 500, it often experiences a short-term bump in its stock price. This is known as the "index effect" and occurs because index funds and ETFs that track the S&P 500 must purchase shares of the newly added company to accurately replicate the index's holdings. Conversely, companies removed from the index may experience downward pressure as those same funds sell their shares.</p>
      <p>It's also important to note that while the S&P 500 is a market-cap-weighted index, there is also an equal-weight version of the index (tracked by ETFs like RSP). In the equal-weight version, every company, regardless of size, has the same weighting (0.2%). Comparing the performance of the traditional market-cap-weighted S&P 500 to the equal-weight version can provide valuable insights into market breadth and whether rallies are being driven by a few large companies or a broad swath of the market.</p>

